00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:05.810
So our sessions and the
summaries of them--

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:13.930
so session number one was
the introduction.

00:01:13.930 --> 00:01:29.370
But I'll start with session two,
was teaching equations.

00:01:29.370 --> 00:01:33.600
Now the fundamental idea I
wanted people to learn in this

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:39.050
one is to help students learn
equations in big chunks.

00:01:39.050 --> 00:01:41.850
So doing derivations
is generally

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:43.270
antithetical to that.

00:01:43.270 --> 00:01:47.120
Because students will just see
the little symbols, and

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:49.430
they'll see a ton and ton and
ton and ton of symbols.

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:52.300
And they're chunk size is much
smaller than you, so you will

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:55.420
overload their short
term memory.

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.870
And they won't really be
understanding, they'll be just

00:01:57.870 --> 00:01:59.900
trying to remember and write
as fast as they can.

00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:09.570
So is that visible,
the orange?

00:02:09.570 --> 00:02:09.810
Yeah?

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:10.560
Great.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:14.180
Oh yeah, you're a good test.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:17.090
So teaching equations, you
want to try and chunk the

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:20.490
equations, because that gives
meaning for the students.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:23.760
So, for example, what
does each term mean?

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:27.330
Why would you expect that term
to show up in the equation?

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:30.770
Those are the kinds of things
that a book generally does not

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:31.910
do very well.

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:35.560
And that's something that you,
as a teacher, actually have a

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:38.480
lot of value to add.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:43.600
Now I just learned about a book
that does try to do this,

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:45.260
which is called A Student's
Guide to Maxwell's Equations.

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:52.270
Does anybody know that book?

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:53.390
Yeah, you know it?

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:56.200
So, it looks fantastic.

00:02:56.200 --> 00:03:00.220
I'm number seven or something
in the queue to get a copy

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:03.120
from the MIT library, which
shows how popular it is.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:04.610
But the way it's organized--

00:03:04.610 --> 00:03:07.130
well, first of all, it's sold
an immense number of copies

00:03:07.130 --> 00:03:13.460
for a technical textbook,
something like 7,000 or

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:15.180
something like that.

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:19.080
So it's a physics best seller.

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:20.730
It's not an Agatha Christie
novel, but

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:22.290
it's really well done.

00:03:22.290 --> 00:03:28.600
And each chapter talks about
one of the equations.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:31.630
So there's four, roughly,
Maxwell's equations.

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:34.820
And there's four chapters,
one per equation.

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:37.670
So it's helping the students
chunk just by the very

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:38.470
structure of the books.

00:03:38.470 --> 00:03:41.950
But most books don't do that,
aren't that well or that

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:44.470
interestingly constructed, and
that thoughtfully constructed,

00:03:44.470 --> 00:03:49.970
so it's something that you, as
a teacher, really should do.

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:51.220
The next one--

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.300
misconceptions.

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:06.170
So why did we spend a whole
session on misconceptions?

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:10.560
Well, it's fundamentally
important, misconceptions,

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:15.650
because if you don't know where
your students are, you

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:17.740
have no chance of bringing
them to where you

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:19.579
want them to go.

00:04:19.579 --> 00:04:22.730
The example that's classic,
that's [? probably ?]

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:25.180
started this whole line of
research about misconceptions,

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:27.990
was students' understanding
of force and motion.

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:30.950
And basically, what you find
is that most peoples'

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.480
intuitive understanding
of force and

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.125
motion is f equals mv.

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:42.110
If you have an object,
you stop pushing

00:04:42.110 --> 00:04:43.890
it, it stops moving.

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:45.950
Force and velocity
are connected.

00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:49.450
If you have a heavier object,
you have to push it harder.

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:52.510
If you have a lighter object,
you push it less.

00:04:52.510 --> 00:04:54.350
So force and mass are connected,
so it looks

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:55.760
like f equals mv.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.360
Whereas, we would like to
teach them f equals ma,

00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:00.460
Newton's Second Law, force
equals mass times

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:01.330
acceleration.

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:05.270
So there's a fundamental
difference there, and if you

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:08.570
don't take account of that,
you'll end up producing just

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:09.320
rote knowledge.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.530
They'll say OK, well whenever
I happen to be in physics

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:16.080
class, I'll use f equals ma, and
I'll just solve problems

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:19.270
symbolically using that
procedure you've told me.

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:21.420
But I don't really believe it,
or understand it, or use it in

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:24.000
my own reasoning, so my
intuition is no longer

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.190
available for reasoning.

00:05:26.190 --> 00:05:29.120
So by taking account of
students' misconceptions and

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:32.180
helping them come to an
intuitive understanding of how

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:33.580
things really work,
you're actually

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:34.630
making them much smarter.

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:36.540
So this is knowing--

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:51.880
so that's knowing how
students think.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.510
So this is pretty much opposite
to behaviorism.

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:02.580
Because you're saying, well, I
really want to peer into how

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:06.200
people are reflecting, and how
their cognition works, what's

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:08.020
going on under the hood.

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:11.000
And behaviorism says, well, no,
all you need to do is look

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:11.810
at the behavior.

00:06:11.810 --> 00:06:15.740
If they're solving problems
correctly, that's fine.

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:18.100
Whereas actually you want to
know, well, why did they solve

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:18.410
it that way?

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:19.930
Is it because they really
understood it or not?

00:06:19.930 --> 00:06:24.060
Did they just say 6 times 3 is
18, because they were told, or

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:24.950
they memorized it?

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:28.720
Or was it because they really
understood it, in which case

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:31.500
they could make a word problem
related to it?

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:35.630
So knowing how students think,
you're actually part of the

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:36.620
cognitive revolution.

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:39.400
And you're actually connecting
to students, directly and

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:42.240
making them much smarter.

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:43.675
Homework and exam questions--

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:59.340
so constructing homework and
exam questions, the main theme

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:01.030
of that was Bloom's Taxonomy.

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:13.260
So this was a hierarchy of goals
that you could have.

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:15.260
So the full name is A Taxonomy
of Educational Objectives.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:20.090
And the ones we're talking
about, if you look at the full

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:21.700
title, it's the cognitive
domain.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:23.560
There's the cognitive
and affective.

00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:27.385
Affective means related to
feelings and emotions.

00:07:27.385 --> 00:07:30.560
This is the cognitive domain
ones I'm talking about here.

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:34.200
So are you asking for
just comprehension?

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:37.000
Are you asking for students
to analyze?

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.410
Are you asking them to
synthesize knowledge?

00:07:39.410 --> 00:07:42.780
What is the level of cognitive
activity that

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:43.990
you're asking for?

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:47.780
And generally, you want
to mix levels.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.730
So you don't want to just
push the students

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:51.980
off a cliff and say--

00:07:56.870 --> 00:07:58.960
the first day in thermodynamics
class, discuss

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:01.010
how the Second Law of
Thermodynamics applies to the

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:03.370
entropy of the universe?

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:05.532
That's just too hard.

00:08:05.532 --> 00:08:08.485
You've pushed them way off the
cliff, and you jumped way too

00:08:08.485 --> 00:08:09.520
high in Bloom's Taxonomy.

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:12.210
You also don't want to just give
them pure comprehension

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:15.480
problems, because they remember
the rule that you're

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:17.080
trying to teach.

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:19.520
Rather, you want to mix them,
and Bloom's Taxonomy gives you

00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:22.470
a structured way of seeing what
level your questions are

00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:26.050
at and making sure you mix
them, so that you prepare

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:28.240
students comprehension
questions, so that they can

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:33.110
later do evaluation questions.

00:08:33.110 --> 00:08:34.360
Course design--

00:08:41.950 --> 00:08:51.030
so for course design, the
big idea is big ideas.

00:08:51.030 --> 00:09:01.590
So you want to organize your
course around some kind of

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:03.260
large ideas.

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:08.500
And ideally, those large ideas
will transfer outside of the

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:09.790
course too.

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:12.300
And if a whole curriculum is
organized around a few large

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:16.580
ideas, for example, waves and
oscillatory motion, you could

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:20.670
also organize a whole bunch of
a physics major around ideas

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:23.040
like that, or conservation.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:28.790
By giving structure to the
curriculum, you turn it away

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:32.010
from just a series of
unconnected facts, like we did

00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:34.900
this topic, that topic, that
topic, that topic, actually

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:37.190
you give it form and
organization.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:40.740
And then it's much more likely
to be built into long lasting

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:42.590
chunks in the students' minds.

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:48.004
So the next one was interactive
teaching.

00:09:57.750 --> 00:10:01.120
The sixth session was
interactive teaching.

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:06.280
And the main theme is that
questioning and reflecting

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:07.740
lead to long lasting learning.

00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:28.230
So I showed you three or four
different time scales on which

00:10:28.230 --> 00:10:30.890
you could be interactive.

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:34.040
A short one is when you ask a
question, you wait 5 seconds.

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:36.830
Or actually some of you
suggested seven, which is

00:10:36.830 --> 00:10:37.650
probably better.

00:10:37.650 --> 00:10:39.910
It's just harder to do, but
it's probably better.

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:42.780
So you wait a certain amount
of time to allow people to

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:44.610
actually formulate questions.

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:48.290
So that promotes interaction
on a short scale.

00:10:48.290 --> 00:10:51.350
You can ask short questions,
one or two minutes, two or

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:53.940
three minutes, with a multiple
choice right in

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:55.470
the middle of lecture.

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:56.950
It gives you feedback.

00:10:56.950 --> 00:10:59.570
So it's related to the
misconceptions one.

00:10:59.570 --> 00:11:01.760
You're learning how students
think, just as

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.010
they answer the questions.

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:14.670
Or on the same time scale, you
can ask the feedback questions

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:16.970
from this sheet at the
end of the lecture.

00:11:16.970 --> 00:11:19.310
So that's also promoting
a space for questions.

00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:22.600
And you can actually see
how successful that is.

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:25.100
There's so many questions,
actually, we could spend two

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:26.760
more sessions answered
all the questions,

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:29.770
which I'm glad about.

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:32.400
Because questioning
and reflecting--

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.430
that's how people make
knowledge their own.

00:11:35.430 --> 00:11:37.320
So the formal name for that
is constructivism.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:40.260
But what you're doing is
you're helping people

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:41.210
construct knowledge.

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:42.940
And you can do this
on a long scale.

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:45.120
Like for example, for the whole
lecture, you can use a

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:48.410
question like the word blocks,
which I showed you earlier.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:51.050
You can actually do that
for an entire lecture.

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:54.645
And actually, we just did that
for entire lecture in my Art

00:11:54.645 --> 00:11:56.050
of Approximation class.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:58.600
Because the word blocks leads
to xylophones, and I brought

00:11:58.600 --> 00:11:59.380
in a xylophone.

00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:02.940
And we can talk about how the
pitches of the thick and thin

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:06.200
wood blocks relate to the
pitches of shorter and longer

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:08.850
xylophone slats.

00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:11.420
So rich examples like that--

00:12:11.420 --> 00:12:12.790
one doesn't have that
many of them.

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:15.380
But when you do have them, you
can actually build an entire

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:16.620
session around them.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:19.490
And it produces all of
these good things.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:23.840
Seven--

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:39.830
lecture planning
and performing.

00:12:39.830 --> 00:12:42.260
So for the planning of the
lecture, just like for the

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:45.160
course, the planning of a
course, you want to organize

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:47.670
it around some kind of big idea,
some kind of thing that

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:49.000
gives it structure.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.870
The whole lecture, you
want an objective.

00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:10.200
For example, by the end of the
lecture, I want students to be

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:13.660
able to explain the origin
of the terms in the

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:14.910
Navier-Stokes equation.

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:20.040
So then you would choose
your activities in

00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:21.830
lecture around this goal.

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:25.620
But that goal, actually just
like the longer scale one for

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:27.680
the whole course, gives
structure to the lecture.

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:29.940
And you know what to put in
and what not to put it.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:34.000
And the lecture planning blank
sheets, or the templates I

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.960
gave you, I posted, you can
use those to that end.

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:41.920
And that's for the
planning part.

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:48.630
And for the performing, I would
say the main thing in

00:13:48.630 --> 00:13:52.840
performing that people don't
normally think about when they

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:54.160
think about teaching
is timing.

00:13:59.860 --> 00:14:03.560
So if you want to create little
bits of suspense and

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:06.450
interest, little bits
of tension,

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:07.780
that are then released.

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:09.960
And you want to do that
on multiple scales--

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:12.630
short and long.

00:14:12.630 --> 00:14:16.240
The interactive teaching
questions from here help do

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:18.400
that, especially if you
have a demonstration.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:21.640
Because people want to know, is
the thick wood block going

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:25.250
to be higher pitch or is it
going to be a lower pitch?

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:26.930
And you'll find that when you
do things like that, the

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:28.850
entire room is dead silent,
because people

00:14:28.850 --> 00:14:29.960
really want to know.

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:34.200
And the way you structure the
questions can promote that.

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:37.630
By having people vote, they've
now made a public commitment,

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:42.330
which then activates the
cognitive dissonance part of

00:14:42.330 --> 00:14:43.580
people's mind.

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:50.580
By making a public commitment,
they've now made their

00:14:50.580 --> 00:14:53.880
internal state more towards the
public state, which is oh,

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:55.290
I want to know what's
going on.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:57.170
And they really do want to
know what's going on.

00:14:57.170 --> 00:15:01.310
So timing-- you can get a lot
of timing ideas from the

00:15:01.310 --> 00:15:03.370
interactive teaching methods.

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:06.310
But timing is really important
for performing.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:10.520
Imagine jokes where people tell
you the punchline first,

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:12.740
and then they tell you
the rest of the joke.

00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:15.480
They don't go over too well, and
most comics, at least most

00:15:15.480 --> 00:15:18.080
successful comics,
don't do that.

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:19.690
But we usually do that
with our teaching.

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:35.680
Blackboards and slides
for teaching--

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:45.110
so the main concepts to think
about there are the chunk size

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:50.540
that students have and how many
spots they have in short

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:51.790
term memory.

00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:57.420
So with the blackboard, you have
many advantages for free,

00:15:57.420 --> 00:16:01.430
which is that on the blackboard,
you don't have to

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:04.950
