00:24:34.790 --> 00:24:37.580
That was never my thing.

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:40.660
And this is so prevalent.

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:43.320
So now, what do you have
to do in that case?

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:45.480
So that's their misconception.

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:47.585
And so number three up there,
you have to really take

00:24:47.585 --> 00:24:49.180
account of that.

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.575
Their way of thinking about math
and physics, the way that

00:24:51.575 --> 00:24:54.115
it was taught to them completely
did not work, and

00:24:54.115 --> 00:24:56.440
it just produced fear
and phobia.

00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:59.530
So now what you have to do is
you have to go around that.

00:24:59.530 --> 00:25:02.090
And so one of the ways actually
Brian Butterworth,

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:05.130
who actually studies this--
he's a professor of

00:25:05.130 --> 00:25:08.110
neurophysiology, in London.

00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:10.680
And I mentioned his book a
couple times, I think, it's

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:15.340
called The Mathematical Brain
or What Counts, depending on

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:17.430
whether it's the English
or American title.

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:23.020
So math phobia a lot caused by
people having a fear that

00:25:23.020 --> 00:25:25.530
there's only one way to
get the right answer.

00:25:25.530 --> 00:25:29.280
So they think they're walking
across a tight rope, and if

00:25:29.280 --> 00:25:33.230
you make it one misstep, then
you fall into the abyss.

00:25:33.230 --> 00:25:35.090
And so, of course, if you
have that conception of

00:25:35.090 --> 00:25:37.620
mathematical reasoning and
problem solving, you're going

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:39.740
to have a lot of fear.

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:40.770
So what you have to
do is you have to

00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:44.090
show people, no, actually--

00:25:44.090 --> 00:25:46.490
right over here.

00:25:46.490 --> 00:25:59.780
So if this was their model, that
if that's the one way to

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:04.050
get to the solution, actually
you want to show them not

00:26:04.050 --> 00:26:18.600
that, and show them
even dead ends.

00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:20.560
Not every method of solution
will work out.

00:26:20.560 --> 00:26:23.660
Some might just end up there,
and some might end up there.

00:26:23.660 --> 00:26:26.490
And some connect to other
methods and get to a solution.

00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:29.750
And even maybe, that's
one solution, but

00:26:29.750 --> 00:26:31.000
maybe there's two.

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:37.300
So you want to show them that
there's robust paths across

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:39.420
the river, let's say.

00:26:39.420 --> 00:26:41.660
You're not trying to, for
example, jump Niagara Falls,

00:26:41.660 --> 00:26:43.980
where one misstep
and down you go.

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:46.080
So that's a way of reducing
the math phobia.

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:48.740
Now that's a particular example,
but that's an example

00:26:48.740 --> 00:26:52.800
of how you have to think
slightly differently for the

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:53.370
adult learner.

00:26:53.370 --> 00:26:55.950
The reason is that they've had
longer time to internalize the

00:26:55.950 --> 00:26:57.250
misconception.

00:26:57.250 --> 00:27:01.430
The high school student, for
example, they haven't

00:27:01.430 --> 00:27:03.930
necessarily formed their
own view of them self.

00:27:03.930 --> 00:27:06.300
And it's less true at the
college level, that people are

00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:08.950
starting to form their view of
self more and more, but it's

00:27:08.950 --> 00:27:10.510
still changeable, especially
in America.

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:13.230
And that's one really excellent
part of the American

00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:14.360
university system.

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:17.060
So you may not realize it if you
come from America, but in

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:19.320
almost every other country in
the world, when you go to

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:23.400
university, you pick your
subject and that's what you do

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.660
for the rest of the
university time.

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:29.200
So England, for example,
it's even before that.

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:31.900
If you want to do physics at
Cambridge, you have to have

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:33.940
done, for the last two years
of high school--

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:35.850
basically everyone who did
physics at Cambridge did

00:27:35.850 --> 00:27:41.120
physics, math, chemistry, and
further maths, I should say.

00:27:41.120 --> 00:27:42.670
So further maths are
just more maths--

00:27:42.670 --> 00:27:47.120
basically like DE calculus.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:51.000
so they did, for the last two
years of school, only math and

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:52.630
physics and chemistry courses.

00:27:52.630 --> 00:27:54.560
And then they go on
to university, and

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:55.880
they do just physics.

00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:58.330
And Cambridge had a radical
innovation on that, which was

00:27:58.330 --> 00:28:01.060
that in the first year, you
didn't do just physics, you

00:28:01.060 --> 00:28:06.320
did physics, math, chemistry,
and maybe a fourth subject.

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:10.390
So that was considered really
very progressive.

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:11.750
And it was compared
to the rest of

00:28:11.750 --> 00:28:13.380
the educational system.

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:16.090
So in Europe, in general, there
isn't that freedom.

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:17.340
So in America, you
still have it.

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:19.560
So the students in college are
still going to be quite

00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:21.760
different from the people who've
basically fixed their

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:24.680
view of them self as bad at
math or bad at whatever.

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:28.200
And that's one of the things
that you change when you're

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.400
thinking about adult learners.

